{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":275,"record_hash":"sha256:839c9fe6199c6dcffb33d042ef45f3b61638919e51476aa7ce30408db11d6edf","timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:22:50.803Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/src/git-meta/notes/atomic-metadata-edits-plan.md\n+# Atomic Metadata Edits Plan\n+\n+## Goal\n+\n+Expand GitMeta's batched edit API so callers can update mixed metadata value\n+types in one all-or-nothing operation.\n+\n+Today `apply_edits` supports appending to lists and adding to sets atomically.\n+That is useful, but callers that need to update scalar metadata in the same\n+logical operation must call `set_value` separately. This creates partial-write\n+failure modes for features that need to keep an index, summary, detail record,\n+and append-only log in sync.\n+\n+The goal is not to design around one downstream feature. The useful primitive is\n+generic:\n+\n+> Given one target, apply several metadata mutations across strings, lists, and\n+> sets as one transaction.\n+\n+## Current Shape\n+\n+Relevant files:\n+\n+- `crates/git-meta-lib/src/types.rs`\n+- `crates/git-meta-lib/src/session_handle.rs`\n+- `crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/lists.rs`\n+- `[REDACTED:entropy].rs`\n+- `crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/metadata.rs`\n+- `crates/git-meta-lib/src/db/mod.rs`\n+\n+Current public edit enum:\n+\n+```rust\n+pub enum MetaEdit<'a> {\n+    ListAppend {\n+        key: &'a str,\n+        entries: &'a [crate::ListEntry],\n+    },\n+    SetAdd {\n+        key: &'a str,\n+        members: &'a [String],\n+    },\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Current transaction behavior:\n+\n+- `SessionTargetHandle::apply_edits` delegates to `Store::apply_edits`.\n+- `Store::apply_edits` validates keys, opens a savepoint, applies each edit, and\n+  commits the savepoint at the end.\n+- If an edit fails, the savepoint rolls back on drop.\n+- `Store::set_value` already exists for string/list/set replacement.\n+- `Store::set` / `set_with_git_ref` already use their own savepoint, and the\n+  savepoint helper is nestable.\n+\n+This means the implementation should be mostly API widening and tests, not a new\n+transaction system.\n+\n+## Proposed API\n+\n+Add a general set-value edit:\n+\n+```rust\n+pub enum MetaEdit<'a> {\n+    ListAppend {\n+        key: &'a str,\n+        entries: &'a [crate::ListEntry],\n+    },\n+    SetAdd {\n+        key: &'a str,\n+        members: &'a [String],\n+    },\n+    SetValue {\n+        key: &'a str,\n+        value: &'a crate::MetaValue,\n+    },\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Add a constructor:\n+\n+```rust\n+impl<'a> MetaEdit<'a> {\n+    pub fn set_value(key: &'a str, value: &'a crate::MetaValue) -> Self {\n+        Self::SetValue { key, value }\n+    }\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Name note: prefer `SetValue` / `set_value` over a string-specific name because\n+`MetaValue` already represents string, list, and set replacement. The operation\n+means \"replace this metadata key with this typed metadata value.\"\n+\n+## Implementation Steps\n+\n+1. Update `MetaEdit`\n+   - Add `SetValue { key, value }`.\n+   - Add a `set_value` constructor.\n+   - Update docs to say `apply_edits` handles mixed metadata edits, not only\n+     list/set edits.\n+\n+2. Update validation in `Store::apply_edits`\n+   - Include `SetValue` in the key extraction match.\n+   - Keep up-front key validation before opening/applying the batch.\n+\n+3. Update edit application in `Store::apply_edits`\n+   - Match `MetaEdit::SetValue { key, value }`.\n+   - Call `self.set_value(target, key, value, email, timestamp)?`.\n+   - Rely on nested savepoints for now unless this causes a concrete issue.\n+\n+4. Update `SessionTargetHandle::apply_edits` docs\n+   - Describe it as applying metadata edits in one transaction.\n+   - Mention list entry timestamp adjustment still applies only to list append\n+     edits.\n+\n+5. Add focused tests\n+   - Mixed success: `SetValue` + `ListAppend` + `SetAdd` all land.\n+   - Mixed rollback: first edit succeeds, later edit fails, and none of the\n+     batch remains.\n+   - Type replacement: `SetValue` can replace a list or set key with a string\n+     and clears stale collection rows/tombstones as normal `set_value` does.\n+   - Existing list append timestamp behavior still works in a mixed batch.\n+\n+6. Run validation\n+   - `cargo fmt`\n+   - Narrow tests first, likely `cargo test -p git-meta-lib apply_edits`\n+   - Then `cargo test -p git-meta-lib`\n+   - If the repo standard requires it, run clippy after tests.\n+\n+## Test Scenarios\n+\n+### Mixed Batch Success\n+\n+Setup:\n+\n+- target: `commit:abc123`\n+- existing list key: `events = [\"old\"]`\n+- existing set key: `event-hashes = {\"hash-0\"}`\n+\n+Batch:\n+\n+- `SetValue(\"summary\", MetaValue::String(\"new summary\"))`\n+- `ListAppend(\"events\", [\"new event\"])`\n+- `SetAdd(\"event-hashes\", [\"hash-1\"])`\n+\n+Assert:\n+\n+- `summary == \"new summary\"`\n+- `events == [\"old\", \"new event\"]`\n+- `event-hashes == {\"hash-0\", \"hash-1\"}`\n+- metadata log has entries for each operation.\n+\n+### Mixed Batch Rollback\n+\n+Setup:\n+\n+- `event-hashes` exists as a string, not a set.\n+\n+Batch:\n+\n+- `SetValue(\"summary\", MetaValue::String(\"should roll back\"))`\n+- `ListAppend(\"events\", [\"should roll back\"])`\n+- `SetAdd(\"event-hashes\", [\"hash-1\"])`\n+\n+The set add should fail with a type mismatch. Assert:\n+\n+- `summary` is absent.\n+- `events` is absent.\n+- `event-hashes` is still the original string.\n+- no metadata log entries remain for rolled-back edits.\n+\n+### Type Replacement In A Batch\n+\n+Setup:\n+\n+- `detail` exists as a list or set.\n+\n+Batch:\n+\n+- `SetValue(\"detail\", MetaValue::String(\"{...json...}\"))`\n+\n+Assert:\n+\n+- `detail` reads back as a string.\n+- stale `list_values` or `set_values` rows for that metadata id are gone.\n+\n+This mostly proves the batched path preserves existing `set_value` semantics.\n+\n+## Compatibility Notes\n+\n+- This is an additive Rust API change.\n+- Existing callers using `ListAppend` and `SetAdd` should continue to compile.\n+- If downstream crates construct `MetaEdit` with exhaustive matches, they will\n+  need to handle the new variant. That is acceptable for a non-exhaustive\n+  internal-ish crate API, but check current consumers before landing.\n+- Do not change the storage format.\n+- Do not change sync or materialization semantics.\n+\n+## Non-Goals\n+\n+- Do not add cross-target transactions in this change. Keep the batch scoped to\n+  one `Target`, matching the current handle model.\n+- Do not add record-specific helpers such as `SetRecord`. Callers can serialize\n+  structured values into a `MetaValue::String` when they need one-key JSON.\n+- Do not add conditional compare-and-swap semantics.\n+- Do not redesign list or set merge behavior.\n+- Do not introduce a path specifically for agent logs or any other downstream\n+  feature.\n+\n+## Design Checks\n+\n+Before implementing, confirm these details in the current tree:\n+\n+- `Store::set_value` uses `Store::set`, which opens a nested savepoint.\n+- `AutoSavepoint` is safe to nest under the savepoint opened by `apply_edits`.\n+- Rollback removes both data rows and `metadata_log` rows written inside the\n+  failed batch.\n+- Large string/git-ref behavior remains a sync/materialization concern and does\n+  not need special handling in `SetValue`.\n+\n+If nested savepoints create noisy or surprising behavior, the fallback is to\n+split the internals:\n+\n+- keep public `set_value` as-is\n+- extract a private `set_value_without_savepoint`\n+- call that private helper from both `set_value` and `apply_edits`\n+\n+Do not start there unless tests show the simpler nested-savepoint approach is\n+wrong.\n+\n+## Suggested PR Shape\n+\n+Keep the PR small:\n+\n+1. Add `MetaEdit::SetValue`.\n+2. Update `apply_edits`.\n+3. Add tests.\n+4. Update docs/comments.\n+\n+Avoid touching sync, serialization, pruning, or CLI behavior unless a test proves\n+the edit API needs it.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:22:50.803Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}